Furthermore, the sensitivity of CCNL-7 for detecting I− was also evaluated. The AQY of CCNL-7 sharply decreased then gradually decreased upon the stepwise increase in the I− concentration (Fig. 6
                        a). The change in AQY was assessed using the following equation: AQY =  − 0.0131 × C0 + 18.62, where C0 is the I− concentration. The relationship exhibited good linearity within the range of 5–150 mg/L. The LOD was 2.58 mg/L at a signal/noise ratio of 3 [57]. At lower concentrations, the fluorescence intensity of CCNL-7 significantly decreased with an increase in the I− concentration (Fig. 6b). The linear relationship between the I0/I − 1 values and the concentration of I− within the range of 0.2–1.0 μg/L with an R2 of 0.9964 was satisfactory. Here, I0 and I were fluorescence emission intensities of CCNL-7 in the absence and presence of I−, respectively. The LOD of CCNL-7 for I− reached 0.09 μg/L. Compared with other reported fluorescent probes (Table 2
                        ), CCNL-7 had a relatively superior LOD and linear range. Thus, CCNL-7 holds promise as an effective fluorescent probe for I−.
